<title><i>Ssa ka Kumm</i> (the eland&apos;s story)</title>
<summary>The hunting of eland and related ceremonies. There are many things the hunter must do to show respect for the eland, as it is a &apos;magic thing&apos; and |kaggen (the Mantis) will try to revive the game and keep it from dying. The verso notes contain further details of these practices. Pages 5359v-5361v contains warnings about the casting of shadows (translated by Dorothea Bleek). </summary><comments>1) p.5316v: this story was told to Dia!kwain by his father (Xaa-ttin), 2) Date on p.5338: 26 September, 3) p.5341v: an explanatory note by Dia!kwain (12 December 1875) on the actions of |kaggen (the Mantis) and how he changes his appearance to make people afraid (like at &apos;Guy Fawkes&apos;), 4) pp.5345v-5348v: see <i>The Mantis and the hunting of eland, </i>5) p.5353 opp: (4 October 1875) the !num !num moth found in Bushmanland in trees (caught at Mowbray, 3 October), 6) pp.5359v-5361v contains warnings about the casting of shadows (translated by Dorothea Bleek), 7) p.5361v: the throwing of shadows; what occurs after striking the eland with its tail, 8) See also <i>Further ceremonies in cutting up eland,</i> 9) This story is found in Books V-17 and V-18</comments><date>September 1875</date><storypages>5317-5353, 5354-5363</storypages><category>Custom and daily life</category><author>Dia!kwain (David Hoesar) (V)</author><keyword><kw>eland</kw><subkw>its story or Ssa ka Kumm</subkw></keyword>
